{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":439818,"duration_api_ms":393488,"num_turns":49,"result":"```json\n{\n  \"outcome\": \"success\",\n  \"completion_round\": 13,\n  \"files_changed\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"src/contexts/workflow_composition/retry_policy.rs\",\n      \"changes\": \"Applied .min(self.backoff_cap) after apply_jitter() so jitter can never push backoff above the configured cap (e.g. 60s × 1.25 = 75s is now re-capped to 60s).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"src/adapters/process_backend.rs\",\n      \"changes\": \"Replaced `!binary.exists()` with `!binary.is_absolute() || !binary.exists()` in spawn ENOENT handler. For bare names returned by resolve_binary (OS PATH lookup), ENOENT always maps to BinaryNotFound since PATH resolution failed. For absolute paths (from explicit search_paths), the exists() check still guards against misclassifying missing-interpreter ENOENT. Updated comment to explain the bare-name vs absolute-path distinction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"tests/unit/retry_policy_test.rs\",\n      \"changes\": \"Added two new tests: (1) jitter_enabled_backoff_stays_within_expected_range — verifies attempt-1 backoff with jitter falls in [3.75s, 6.25s) across 20 samples; (2) jitter_never_exceeds_backoff_cap — verifies no jittered backoff exceeds 60s for attempts 1–10 across 20 samples each.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"tests/unit/process_backend_test.rs\",\n      \"changes\": \"Added clean_timeout_teardown_yields_timeout_without_warning test — spawns a sleeping process, triggers timeout, asserts FailureClass::Timeout and absence of 'teardown not confirmed' warning in details.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"amendments_addressed\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"description\": \"Added three new test functions covering jitter range validation, jitter cap enforcement, and clean teardown → Timeout classification with no teardown warning.\",\n      \"resolution\": \"Tests added to retry_policy_test.rs (jitter_enabled_backoff_stays_within_expected_range, jitter_never_exceeds_backoff_cap) and process_backend_test.rs (clean_timeout_teardown_yields_timeout_without_warning). Unclean teardown (confirm_teardown returning false) cannot be tested end-to-end without kernel-level uninterruptible sleep simulation since SIGKILL is uncatchable — the clean path is verified instead.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"description\": \"binary.exists() on bare names checks CWD not PATH — unreliable for OS PATH lookup.\",\n      \"resolution\": \"Changed condition to `!binary.is_absolute() || !binary.exists()`. Bare names (from resolve_binary with no search_paths) always classify ENOENT as BinaryNotFound since the OS PATH lookup failed. Absolute paths (from explicit search_paths resolution) retain the exists() guard to distinguish missing-binary from missing-interpreter ENOENT.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"description\": \"Jitter can push backoff above backoff_cap (60s × 1.25 = 75s).\",\n      \"resolution\": \"Added `.min(self.backoff_cap)` after `Self::apply_jitter(capped)` in backoff_for_attempt(). The new jitter_never_exceeds_backoff_cap test validates this across attempts 1–10.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"description\": \"Same root cause as amendment 2 — binary.exists() resolves relative to CWD for bare names like 'claude', checking ./claude instead of PATH.\",\n      \"resolution\": \"Resolved together with amendment 2 via the is_absolute() guard.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"verification\": {\n    \"tests_passed\": true,\n    \"test_count\": 683,\n    \"clippy_clean\": true,\n    \"fmt_clean\": true,\n    \"command\": \"cargo test && cargo clippy -- -D warnings && cargo fmt --check\"\n  }\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"2ab56341-dc03-426c-ace5-dda05f3b0827","total_cost_usd":3.0209050000000004,"usage":{"input_tokens":102,"cache_creation_input_tokens":212650,"cache_read_input_tokens":2251989,"output_tokens":11896,"server_tool_use":{"we